superMiscConds.notes:
No unsupervised contact with minors (males or females beneath the age of 18) without agent's expressed knowledge and approval.
No contact with J.P., C.J., or M.J.
No contact with K.M. without her consent, without her mom's consent, or without agent's consent, until she turns 18.
No possession or use of pornography.
No possession or use of computers, cell phones, or other electronic devices with access to the Internet without agent's expressed knowledge and approval.
No use or possession of alcohol or illegal street drugs or paraphernalia.
No use or possession of prescription drugs, except drugs specifically prescribed for the offender, and then take such drugs in their proper therapeutic dose.

Pay costs of supervision.
Follow all rules of extended supervision.
Undergo any and all treatments/programming recommended by agent.
Complete sex offender programming to agent's satisfaction.
Register as sex offender and comply with sex offender registry requirements wherever he lives.

(9:58 AM case called.) Defendant Dennis E. McNabb in court. Attorney Cole Daniel Ruby in court for Dennis E. McNabb. Attorney Ellen Krahn appeared by video for Dennis E. McNabb. Attorney Karin Jonch-Clausen in court for Dennis E. McNabb. Attorney Loralee Clark in court for State of Wisconsin.
Attorney Ruby advises the defense will present two witnesses today. Attorney Ruby also advises submitted a couple document via the e-filing and parties discuss exhibits and how to best handle.
Attorney Ruby advises has spoken with the defendant regarding attorney client privileges and advises the defendant will waive the right to attorney client privilege regarding information exchanged with Attorney Krahn.
Court has colloquy with the defendant regarding attorney client privilege and the defendant waives right to attorney client privilege. Court accepts the defendant's waiver to attorney client privilege regarding information exchanged with Attorney Krahn.
Defense calls Attorney Ellen Krahn of the Appellate Division of the Assistant State Public Defender Office, who is sworn and testifies.
(Off record to have exhibits marked.)
Attorney Jonch-Clausen moves to admit exhibit #1. No objection by the State. Exhibit #1 received.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen moves to admit exhibit #2. No objection by the State. Exhibit #2 received.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen moves to admit exhibit #3. No objection by the State. Exhibit #3 received.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen moves to admit exhibit #4. No objection by the State. Exhibit #4 received.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen moves to admit exhibit #5. No objection by the State. Exhibit #5 received.
State conducts cross-examination of Attorney Krahn.
Attorney Ruby makes note of documents provided as exhibits and Attorney Ruby advises also received notes from Attorney Krahn that were notes from while she was still working on the case which have not been provided to the Court as they are seen as confidential communication with the defendant.
State continues with cross-examination of Attorney Krahn.
State makes demand for discovery of any notes the defense has that was between Attorney Krahn and the defendant, based on the defendant having waived right to attorney client privilege.
Court orders the documents be turned over for an in camera inspection.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen conducts re-direct of Attorney Krahn. Witness excused.
Attorney Ruby mentions notes received from Attorney Krahn and relays his knowledge on the notes. (Court is provided with the documents by Attorney Ruby for in camera inspection.)
Attorney Jonch-Clausen calls defendant Dennis E. McNabb, who is sworn and testifies.
State conducts cross-examination of defendant Dennis McNabb.
Attorney Jonch-Clausen conducts re-direct of defendant Dennis McNabb. Witness excused.
(Off record for the Judge to review the in camera inspection documents.)
Court notes there are 4 segments to the in camera inspection documents and there is nothing in those documents which would be relevant to today's hearing.
Court orders documents are returned to Attorney Ruby who will e-file the documents and once e-filed, documents will be sealed.
State has no witnesses or evidence, just argument.
Attorney Ruby makes argument Attorney Krahn failed to do her job in the appeal process and requests the Court find ineffective assistance of counsel and the appeal rights be reinstated to the defendant.
State makes argument Attorney Krahn was ineffective however, makes argument the defendant failed to assist in his own appeal process and provides reasoning. State requests the petition be denied.
Court will put findings in writing and provide to the Court of Appeals.

IT IS ORDERED that this matter is remanded to the circuit court to conduct an evidentiary hearing and enter findings of fact relevant to both the ineffective assistance allegation and the State's possible laches defense. The circuit court shall have sixty days to hold a hearing and to produce detailed written factual findings. Within five days after the written findings have been made, the clerk of circuit court shall transmit a record of those findings to this court along with any documents that were submitted to the court during remand. 
IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that the parties shall have ten days after the record on remand has been transmitted here to advise this court whether either party will be requesting a transcript of the hearing, or whether they will agree to rely upon the written findings and materials from the hearing. If necessary, this court will set additional deadlines relating to the production of the transcript and filing of a supplement to the record. This court will then either make the ultimate determination as to whether to issue a writ or order additional responses from the parties based upon the circuit court's findings.
IT IS ORDERED that the petitioner may file a reply not exceeding ten pages by no later than Marc 2, 2022.
IT IS ORDERED that the time for filing the respondent's response is extended to February 4, 2022.
IT IS ORDERED that, within fourteen days of the date of this order, the respondent shall file a response to the petition under WIS. STAT. Rule 809.51 (2).
